    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. so what actually causes the change in color specifically? like is it just the heat, or is there a specific byproduct that makes it look brown? i want to make sure i can explain the actual mechanism on the test.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The color change is a direct result of the various compounds formed during the Maillard reaction, not just the heat itself. The heat is the catalyst, but the actual brown pigments are complex molecules called melanoidins. These melanoidins are high-molecular-weight polymers that develop as the amino acids and sugars react, and they are what give that beautiful, deep brown hue to roasted or seared foods. It's a chemical cascade, not just a simple color shift.",
      "source": "target",
