      "content": "Absolutely, moisture content is a huge variable, as is pH level, which can really throw the reaction off track. If your food is too wet, the water will absorb the heat energy, essentially keeping the surface temperature too low for the Maillard reaction to properly begin. A high water content can keep the food simmering rather than searing, which is a critical difference. You want a surface that can reach those high temperatures quickly for the browning to occur.",
